---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro'
import SectionHero from '../../components/SectionHero.astro'
import DocsMeta from '../../components/DocsMeta.astro'
import Callout from '../../components/Callout.astro'
import Steps from '../../components/Steps.astro'
import { Tabs } from '../../components/Tabs'
import { ThemedShot } from '../../components/ThemedShot'
import { withBase } from '../../lib/path'

const installSnippet = `# In your local Tome checkout:
./skills/scribe/install.sh

# That symlinks skills/scribe into ~/.claude/skills/scribe so Claude Code
# picks up the /scribe slash command on next launch.`

const configSnippet = `# ~/.config/tome/scribe.json — multi-profile config
{
  "profiles": {
    "dev": {
      "base_url": "http://localhost:8080",
      "token":    "tome_dev_…"
    },
    "prod": {
      "base_url": "https://tome.example.com",
      "token":    "tome_prod_…"
    }
  },
  "default": "dev"
}`

const ingestSnippet = `# In Claude Code:
/scribe ~/Downloads/manga-batch
# → extracts metadata, dedupes by hash, ingests, fetches candidates`

const updateSnippet = `# Refresh metadata on existing books by natural-language query
/scribe update "Berserk volumes 1 through 10"
/scribe update "everything in the Manga library by Kentaro Miura"`

const auditSnippet = `# Scan for weak metadata + offer fixes
/scribe audit                     # everything
/scribe audit manga              # only Manga library / type
/scribe audit "Vinland Saga"     # only the Vinland Saga series`

const seriesSnippet = `# Fill series-level metadata (status + arcs) from LLM knowledge
/scribe series "Berserk"
/scribe series "One Piece"`
---
<DocsLayout title="Scribe (CLI)" description="Batch-ingest ebooks, fetch metadata, and audit your library from Claude Code with the /scribe skill.">
  <SectionHero section="integrations" />
  <h1>Scribe</h1>
  <p>
    Scribe is Tome's Claude Code Skill — an LLM-driven ingest and metadata tool that runs as a
    slash command inside Claude Code. It dedupes by content hash, looks up canonical
    series/author/type from existing books, fetches metadata candidates, applies high-confidence
    matches automatically, and surfaces ambiguous ones for review.
  </p>
  <DocsMeta />

  <Callout variant="warning" title="Alpha — expect breakage">
    Scribe is under active development. Command syntax, config format, and the auto-apply
    thresholds may change between versions. If you're going to use it on a library you care
    about, dry-run on a copy first.
  </Callout>

  <Callout variant="info" title="Power-user feature">
    Scribe is meant for people running Tome who also use Claude Code. If neither of those
    sentences describes you, the regular <a href={withBase("/docs/bindery")}>Bindery</a> drop-folder
    workflow does most of the same things — just without the LLM-assisted matching.
  </Callout>

  <h2>Install</h2>
  <Steps>
    <li>Make sure Claude Code is installed locally.</li>
    <li>From your Tome checkout, run the install script — it symlinks <code>skills/scribe</code> into <code>~/.claude/skills/scribe</code>.</li>
    <li>Restart Claude Code. <code>/scribe</code> appears as a slash command.</li>
  </Steps>

  <pre><code>{installSnippet}</code></pre>

  <h2>Authentication</h2>
  <p>
    Scribe needs an <a href={withBase("/docs/api-tokens")}>API token</a> to talk to your Tome server. Issue
    one in <strong>Settings → API tokens</strong>, then drop it into
    <code>~/.config/tome/scribe.json</code>.
  </p>

  <pre><code>{configSnippet}</code></pre>

  <p>
    Profiles let you point Scribe at multiple Tome instances. When more than one profile is
    defined, Scribe asks which to use before every run — it never guesses with "dev" then
    blasts your prod library.
  </p>

  <h2>The four modes</h2>
  <Tabs client:load tabs={[
    { label: '/scribe <path>',          code: ingestSnippet },
    { label: '/scribe update <query>',  code: updateSnippet },
    { label: '/scribe audit [scope]',   code: auditSnippet },
    { label: '/scribe series <name>',   code: seriesSnippet },
  ]} />

  <h3>Ingest — <code>/scribe &lt;path&gt;</code></h3>
  <p>
    Walks a folder, extracts metadata from each file (EPUB OPF, CBZ ComicInfo.xml, PDF info),
    deduplicates against existing books by content hash, looks up canonical
    author/series/book-type from siblings already in your library, then POSTs each new book to
    <code>/api/books/ingest</code>. Per book, Scribe fetches description and cover candidates
    from Hardcover / Google Books / Open Library — high-confidence matches auto-apply, ambiguous
    ones get surfaced for your review.
  </p>
  <div class="docs-shot-bare">
    <ThemedShot client:load name="scribe-ingest" alt="Sample /scribe ingest terminal output" />
  </div>

  <h3>Update — <code>/scribe update &lt;query&gt;</code></h3>
  <p>
    Re-fetches metadata for existing books matching a natural-language query. Scribe shows a diff
    before applying — old vs new title, description, cover URL — so you can reject bad matches.
  </p>
  <div class="docs-shot-bare">
    <ThemedShot client:load name="scribe-update" alt="Sample /scribe update terminal output" />
  </div>

  <h3>Audit — <code>/scribe audit [scope]</code></h3>
  <p>
    Scans your library for weak metadata (missing description, missing year, missing cover) and
    for series-name drift (volumes that don't agree on the canonical series spelling). For
    missing descriptions, Scribe falls back to a web search on Goodreads / Wikipedia / the
    publisher's site when the metadata APIs come up empty. Fixes are batched into a single
    approve-or-reject pass.
  </p>
  <p>
    Two specialised passes: <code>/scribe audit years</code> compares stored years against Open
    Library's first-publication year (catching reprint years on classics), and
    <code>/scribe audit editions</code> finds books whose stored ISBN belongs to the <em>wrong
    edition</em> of their series — a light novel carrying its manga adaptation's ISBN — and
    proposes the correct edition's ISBN, publisher, year and description.
  </p>
  <div class="docs-shot-bare">
    <ThemedShot client:load name="scribe-audit" alt="Sample /scribe audit terminal output" />
  </div>

  <h3>Series — <code>/scribe series &lt;name&gt;</code></h3>
  <p>
    Fills <code>SeriesMeta</code> (status: ongoing / finished / hiatus) and creates Arc records
    from LLM knowledge of the series. Good for Berserk-class long runners where defining arcs
    by hand is tedious.
  </p>
  <div class="docs-shot-bare">
    <ThemedShot client:load name="scribe-series" alt="Sample /scribe series terminal output" />
  </div>

  <Callout variant="tip" title="Run audit before update">
    The typical workflow is: <code>/scribe &lt;path&gt;</code> for fresh imports, then
    occasionally <code>/scribe audit</code> to clean up the long tail, then <code>/scribe
    update</code> for targeted refreshes when you notice a series with bad metadata.
  </Callout>
</DocsLayout>
